'To know that I have done everything I can – I tried to help – I said sorry – I feel that I've redeemed myself as much as I can and I hope they got the answers to find the closure as well.'

When asked how others involved in the prank had been able to put the tragedy behind them, Ms Greig simply replied that people handle situations differently.

'Some people were able to just move on from that – I wasn’t – it deeply affected me for a long time and when you are the face of blame publicly you believe it,' she said.

'As well, knowing Jacintha herself has written my name in that suicide note and blamed me directly – you hold yourself responsible.'

Ms Greig spoke of how the incident had taken its toll on her over the past two and a half years.

'It took every bit of strength and every bit of support to get through that but you have a choice you can keep fighting or you can let it just take you over and I wanted to fight - life is so precious,' she said.

'I wanted to try to get better and a part of that was going to the inquest and saying sorry and helping the family out so combined I feel I’ve got everything so I can truly move forward.' 

